The issue with the program is that it should print "apply", not "skip". The
The condition `request.priority > 5` is evaluating to `true`, so the progra
program is executing the inner true branch and printing "skip". 

Here's the corrected Tundra source code:

```tundra
val request = {
  enabled: true,
  priority: 9
};

if (request.enabled) {
  if (request.priority > 5) {
    print("apply");
  } else {
    print("queue");
  }
} else {
  print("disabled");
}
```
This Tundra program should now correctly print "apply" when run, assuming t
that `request.enabled` is `true` and `request.priority` is `9`. If `request
`request.enabled` were false or if `request.priority` was less than or equa
equal to 5, the corresponding message would be printed instead.
